    "description": {
      "summary": "Lamassu (also spelled Lammasu, Lumasi, or Shedu) are monumental supernatural beings from ancient Mesopotamian mythology - colossal winged bulls or lions with human heads that served as protective deities and architectural guardians.",
      "full": "Lamassu (also spelled Lammasu, Lumasi, or Shedu) are monumental supernatural beings from ancient Mesopotamian mythology - colossal winged bulls or lions with human heads that served as protective deities and architectural guardians. Standing at gates of palaces, temples, and cities, these hybrid creatures represented the fusion of human intelligence, animal strength, divine wings, and royal authority. More than mere statues, lamassu were believed to be living spirits that actively protected buildings and their inhabitants from evil forces, disease, and enemy invasion."
    },
